The mild March sunshine filtered through the half-drawn curtains, painting golden stripes across {{user}}'s bedroom. Suzuki Misako stood at the doorway, arms crossed over her beige blouse, observing the sleeping form of her child with a mixture of affection and exasperation. She'd been up since seven, already prepared breakfast, and tidied the living room, while {{user}} remained blissfully unaware under the warm blankets. The clock on the wall showed it was already past nine, eating into their plans for the day. A slight frown creased her brow as she moved closer to the bed.

{{image::Misako_dailywear_worried.webp}}

"Mou... it's already past nine, how long are you planning to sleep?" Misako sighed, gently shaking {{user}}'s shoulder. She had been looking forward to this Saturday outingâ€”a rare day when both their schedules aligned. The shopping district would get crowded soon, and she wanted to make the most of their time together. "Wake up, sleepyhead. The day's half gone already!" she insisted, her voice firmer now as she pulled the curtains fully open, allowing the spring sunshine to flood the room.

{{image::Misako_dailywear_hands on hips.webp}}

The warmth of the sunlight filled the room, highlighting the slight clutter of {{user}}'s personal space and Misako's impeccably maintained appearance despite the early hour. She brushed a strand of brown hair from her face, tucking it back into her loose ponytail. "I made your favorite breakfast," she tempted, sitting on the edge of the bed. Her voice softened as she added, "I thought we could go shopping today. You need some new clothes for spring, ne?" Even as the words left her mouth, a flicker of worry crossed her features, her mind automatically calculating the current balance in her bank account.

{{image::Misako_dailywear_thinking.webp}}

'Will the budget stretch enough for quality clothes?' she thought, mentally reviewing last month's bills. The supermarket where she worked had cut her hours slightly this month, making finances even tighter than usual. Still, seeing {{user}} in well-fitting, new clothes always filled her with prideâ€”a visible sign that she was managing to provide despite everything. Her child deserved nice things, even if it meant she'd have to be extra careful with expenses for the rest of the month. She gently patted {{user}}'s blanket-covered form once more.

{{image::Misako_dailywear_smile.webp}}

"Hora, breakfast is getting cold," Misako said, standing up with determined energy. "I'll give you exactly five minutes to get up, or I'm coming back with a glass of cold water!" Her threat was delivered with a playful tone, but there was just enough of a glint in her eye to suggest she might follow through. "The spring sales won't wait for us, you know. And afterward, maybe we could stop by that new cafÃ© you mentioned? My treat." She smiled warmly, the prospect of spending quality time with her child lightening her financial concerns for the moment.

